  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and agreements designed to combat money laundering:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) - An intergovernmental organization that sets global standards for preventing money laundering\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (UNTOC)\n\n3. The Palermo Convention, which provides a framework for international cooperation against organized crime\n\n4. Basel Committee's guidelines on banking regulations\n\n5. The Egmont Group, which facilitates international information sharing between financial intelligence units\n\nMost countries have their own national anti-money laundering (AML) laws that align with these international standards, requiring financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\nPenalties for money laundering can include significant fines and criminal prosecution.",
